{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5e2aedc-a666-4818-bfa5-a60c12cff437","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- Makes this a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — tells `dotnet pack` to produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will type (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType=Exe`** — required for tools.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimal setup. Want me to scaffold the project or modify an existing `.csproj`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b80aa3ca-85af-48f5-af3c-63197adc86b7","outputTokens":504,"requestId":"5C50:D447C:1D28FF3:204A355:69FA93BA"},"id":"79de9736-0e4d-42c8-9427-85647e9e3a1d","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:05:08.919Z","parentId":"2fbae6b2-927c-4435-a8d1-67ed5577156b"}
